ced that the site had hired Dasha Burns, the 32-year-old NBC News political=
 correspondent, to serve as White House bureau chief. On one level, the hir=
e seemed like another garden-variety, post-election trade window acquisitio=
n, albeit dressed up with typical, avuncular Harrisian hyperbole: Politico =
had been in =E2=80=9Curgent and lively conversations with dozens of talente=
d journalists,=E2=80=9D the elder statesman wrote. =E2=80=9CWe are organizi=
ng for impact,=E2=80=9D he declared. And then there was=E2=80=94wait for
it=E2=80=94that old Politico internal memo standby: =E2=80=9CIn many ways, =
Dasha was born for this moment.=E2=80=9D Generals have sent soldiers to the=
ir deaths with less.

In any event, Dasha=E2=80=99s move is indicative of the lame-duck season re=
calibration of the political media industry at large. By Dasha=E2=80=99s ow=
n admission, the move from rising broadcast star to digital bureau chief is=
 =E2=80=9Cunconventional.=E2=80=9D In a brief conversation on Wednesday, sh=
e acknowledged that she was =E2=80=9Cnot a D.C. cat,=E2=80=9D had previousl=
y been averse to moving from Brooklyn to Washington, and that she had not b=
een anticipating this kind of role after years on various campaign trails. =
