b offer from NBC News, I=E2=80=99m told, was as a congressional reporter. I=
nstead, she opted to =E2=80=9Csee the [Trump] story through=E2=80=9D at the=
 White House, and to do so with a more august title for an organization she=
 said was =E2=80=9Con the forefront of what
journalism can look like.=E2=80=9D (She and Harris are peas in a pod=E2=80=
=A6)

Dasha, largely an unknown in the industry, was certainly a rising star insi=
de NBC News, and several people at 30 Rock and 400 North Cap texted me on W=
ednesday to bemoan her departure, which they attributed to bad management. =
To her credit, Dasha may have been young enough to understand that televisi=
on is no longer the be-all and end-all of political journalism. =E2=80=9CIt=
=E2=80=99s what I grew up in, but I want to be as forward-looking as possib=
le,=E2=80=9D she told me. =E2=80=9CI think it=E2=80=99s now more important =
than ever for individual journalists to be able to flex all of those separa=
