n:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">noted</a></u> last week. Indeed, the=
 fact that she was even under consideration may have simply been an attempt=
 to placate her fellow <i>Post </i>veterans. Either way, Matea never got to
meet with Bezos, who has historically held in-person interviews with execut=
ive editor candidates. <br/><br/>To that end, Matea=E2=80=99s departure to =
the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s longtime rival was <i>yet</i> another blow to mor=
ale for the already dispirited newsroom=E2=80=94=E2=80=9Cdevastating,=E2=80=
=9D per <i>Post </i>columnist <b>Karen Tumulty</b>,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ca=
 profound loss,=E2=80=9D according to national editor <b>Phil Rucker</b>. M=
eanwhile, many other <i>Post </i>journalists now seem to be loose in the sa=
ddle and considering their options. When asked if there were any indication=
s of whom the next editor might be, one senior staffer replied only, =E2=80=
=9CNo idea. Everyone is in a state of grief.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/><i>Grief </i=
>is the operative word here. The <i>Post</i>, after all, has been in a larg=
ely uninterrupted fugue state since the late spring when, <i>you know</i>, =
Lewis defenestrated <b>Sally Buzbee</b>, lost his top choice for editor to =
an internal rebellion, and nearly saw his own epitaph written in the
process. As they wait and mourn, however, the Posties would be wise to <u><=
